    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Scout Traditions: To Uphold or Not?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jon Wartes letter, commenting on Sept 3 editorial, says Boy Scouts' ban on homosexuals may lessen or erase the esteem in which Eagle Scouts are held by colleges and employers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Discrimination by the Scouts'' (editorial, Sept. 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Discrimination by the Scouts'' (editorial, Sept. 3):</p>
        <p>Eagle Scouts have always used their rank as a kind of character reference when filling out applications for college, scholarships and jobs. The tradition of scouting being what it was, the rank of Eagle came to be known as of great value.</p>
        <p>Yet I wonder if listing the Eagle rank on applications will now raise questions as to whether the applicant is intolerant, coming from an organization that proclaims some people less worthy than others.</p>
        <p>Will companies be as willing to give scholarships and jobs to Eagle Scouts? I would want seriously to consider how the applicant might fit into the profile of my company if I were being asked to hire a Scout, especially if my company had a nondiscrimination policy that included sexual orientation.</p>
        <p>JON WARTES  Woodinville, Wash., Sept. 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
